  "business_context": "Price List records solve the multi-pricing problem. A single product rarely has a single price — partners get one price, government accounts get another, end users get a third, distributors a fourth. Price Lists let the organization define each pricing tier as its own object, then associate Products with Price Lists via per-list price entries. A quote or order references a specific Price List, which determines which prices apply to its line items. Salesforce models this as Pricebook2 (the price list) + PricebookEntry (the per-product price within a price list). HubSpot is simpler — single price per Product. EspoCRM has a separate Price Book entity. CiviCRM has Price Sets used for event-registration pricing rather than B2B pricing tiers. Nonprofit deployments rarely use Price Lists; they appear in nonprofits with paid-service motions (training, ticketing). When interviewing clients, surface \"Price List\" by asking whether the same product needs to have different prices for different customer types or in different scenarios. If yes, target backend's price-list capability matters significantly; if all customers pay the same price, this entity is unnecessary.",
  "catalog_id": "price-list",
